<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
The third letter of the Latin and English alphabets. The form of the uppercase "C" derives from the North Semitic letter <em>ghimel</em>, as well as the Greek <em>gamma</em>. It came to the Romans through the Etruscans, in whose language there was no true distinction between the "g" sound and the hard "c" (or "k") sound. In Latin, the "C" was used exclusively as a "K" sound. The forms of the uppercase "C" and lowercase "c" were both originally more angular, resembling the uppercase Greek <em>gamma</em>, and eventually obtained their curved shape in Rome. 
</p>
